article.description: Erica Allenspach scored a career-high 22 points and Julianne Viani also had 22 to help Marist beat Canisius 78-63 on Sunday and win the Metro Atlantic Athletic Conference championship.
article.headline: Allenspach, Viani lead Red Foxes past Golden Griffins for MAAC championship
article.linkText: Marist claims MAAC, fourth straight NCAA berth
article.story:
ALBANY, N.Y. -- Getting to the NCAA tournament is still special for Julianne Viani and her Marist teammates, even though she's been there every year of her career.

Viani scored 22 points and earned tournament MVP honors to help Marist beat Canisius 78-63 on Sunday and win the Metro Atlantic Athletic Conference championship.

"It has been an awesome ride," Viani said. "It hasn't gotten old, if anyone ever asks me that. You always want to raise the bar."

This will be the Red Foxes' fourth straight trip to the NCAA tournament. They advanced to the round of 16 in 2007 before falling to Tennessee, and lost in the second round last season to LSU.

"Out of all the championships we've won this was the most rewarding," Marist coach Brian Giorgis said. "This was the most special. I walk out of my hotel room today and the trainer says we have three kids throwing up. I thought these kids really gutted it out today."

Marist played without Lynzee Johnson, who had 16 points in the semifinal win over Iona and 11 in the quarterfinal victory over Loyola, Md. She was sidelined by the flu, which has been running through the Red Foxes.

Marist (29-3) has advanced to the championship game of the MAAC tournament in each of the past six seasons. The top seed started their run in 2004 by beating the Golden Griffins. The two teams also met for the 2005 title and Canisius came away with a one-point win. Those were the Golden Griffins' only previous appearances in the title game.

"Having them in our conference has made us better," Canisius coach Terry Zeh said. "It's helped with recruiting and every day in summer workouts it's made us want to improve."

Marie Warner had 17 points and 10 rebounds to lead Canisius (24-8). Brittane Russell added 14 points and 12 rebounds.

Erica Allenspach had a career-high 22 points for Marist. Rachele Fitz, the conference's player of the year for the second straight season, added 18 points and 14 rebounds. She had 29 points and a career-high 18 rebounds in a 76-69 victory over Iona in the semifinals.

Second-seeded Canisius advanced to the championship game by beating Fairfield 62-55 on Saturday. The Golden Griffins set a tournament record with 12 3-pointers in their quarterfinal victory over Niagara.

Canisius split its two regular season meetings with Marist, losing at home by 18 in December before stunning the Red Foxes 68-60 in early February.

"There are two things you can definitely count in," Zeh said. "In the winter time it snows in Buffalo and in March you have to go through Marist to win this league."

Marist made 10 3-pointers, including four each by Viani and Allenspach.

The Red Foxes were struggling early in the second half and only led by six. That's when Viani and Allenspach took over.

"I looked at Erica and told her we got to step up," Viani said. "Obviously Rachele's going to be Rachele. Erica hit that 3 and we went on a run."

Leading 49-43, Marist went on a 17-6 spurt to put the game away. Viani started it with a 3-pointer, and her four-point play made it 61-47 with 9:33 left.

Canisius got no closer than 12 the rest of the game.

Marist, which has won its last 73 games when scoring over 70 points, built a 32-24 halftime advantage behind a 17-3 burst midway through the first half. The Red Foxes held the Golden Griffins without a field goal during the spurt and Viani had seven points, including a deep 3-pointer with the shot clock running down that made it 28-13.

"They made a couple bomb 3s at the buzzer of the shot clock that hurt us," Zeh said. "The timing of three or four of the 3s were backbreakers. When you guarded so well for that possession, it hurts."

Russell finally ended the drought for Canisius, hitting her own 3-pointer with 5:28 left in the half. That shot put the junior over 1,000 points in her career, making her the 19th player in school history to reach that milestone.

The 3-pointer also started a 11-4 run by Canisius to close the half.
